9 FLOOR SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to the Oklahoma State Bureau of
Investigation; amending 74 O.S. 2021, Sections 150.5,
11 150.7, and 150.11, which relate to investigations,
powers and duties of the Director of the Oklahoma
12 State Bureau of Investigation, and evidentiary
property; clarifying confidentiality provisions;
13 stating certain records not subject to subpoena or
subpoena duces tecum; authorizing disclosure of
14 certain statistical data; authorizing Director to
enter into certain agreements; authorizing Director
15 to digitally store and dispose of certain records;
authorizing Director to accept certain monies to be
16 deposited in certain fund; authorizing certain
evidence disposal; requiring certain affidavit;
17 clarifying property sale provisions; permitting
refusal to sell property under certain circumstance;
18 updating statutory language and references; and
providing an effective date.
19
20
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 74 O.S. 2021, Section 150.5, is
23 amended to read as follows:
24
Req. No. 3736 Page 1

1 Section 150.5. A. 1. Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation
2 investigations not covered under Section 150.2 of this title shall
3 be initiated at the request of the following persons:
4 a. the Governor,
5 b. the Attorney General,
6 c. the Council on Judicial Complaints upon a vote by a
7 majority of the Council,
8 d. the chair of any Legislative Investigating Committee
9 legislative investigating committee which has been
10 granted subpoena powers by resolution, upon
11 authorization by a vote of the majority of the
12 Committee committee,
13 e. the Director of the Department of Human Services, or
14 designee, as authorized by Section 1-2-105 of Title
15 10A of the Oklahoma Statutes, or
16 f. a district court judge as authorized by Section 1-2-
17 103 of Title 10A of the Oklahoma Statutes.
18 2. Requests for investigations shall be submitted in writing
19 and shall contain specific allegations of wrongdoing under the laws
20 of the State of Oklahoma this state.
21 B. The Governor may initiate special background investigations
22 with the written consent of the person who is the subject of the
23 investigation.
24
Req. No. 3736 Page 2

1 C. The chair of any Senate committee which is fulfilling the
2 statutory responsibility for approving nominations made by the
3 Governor may, upon a vote by a majority of the committee and with
4 the written consent of the person who is to be the subject of the
5 investigation, initiate a special background investigation of any
6 nominee for the Oklahoma Horse Racing Commission as established by
7 Section 201 of Title 3A of the Oklahoma Statutes or any nominee for
8 the Board of Trustees board of trustees of the Oklahoma Lottery
9 Commission as established by Section 704 of Title 3A of the Oklahoma
10 Statutes. The Bureau shall submit a report to the committee within
11 thirty (30) days of the receipt of the request. Any consideration
12 by the committee of a report from the Bureau shall be for the
13 exclusive use of the committee and shall be considered only in
14 executive session.
15 D. 1. All records relating to any investigation being
16 conducted by the Bureau, including any records of laboratory
17 services provided to law enforcement agencies pursuant to paragraph
18 1 of subsection A of Section 150.2 of this title, shall be
19 confidential and privileged and shall not be open to the public or
20 to the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation Commission except as
21 provided in Section 150.4 of this title; provided, however, officers
22 and agents of the Bureau may disclose, at the discretion of the
23 Director of the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation, such
24 investigative information to:
Req. No. 3736 Page 3

1 a. officers and agents of federal, state, county, tribal,
2 or municipal law enforcement agencies and to district
3 attorneys, in the furtherance of criminal
4 investigations prosecutorial entities for the purpose
5 of criminal investigations and prosecutions within
6 their respective jurisdictions,
7 b. employees of the Department of Human Services in the
8 furtherance of child abuse investigations, and
9 c. appropriate accreditation bodies for the purposes of
10 the Bureau’s obtaining or maintaining accreditation.
11 2. Any unauthorized disclosure of any information contained in
12 the confidential files of the Bureau, not otherwise prepared for the
13 purpose of statistical data as referenced in this section, shall be
14 a misdemeanor. The person or entity authorized to initiate
15 investigations in this section, and the Attorney General in the case
16 of investigations initiated by the Insurance Commissioner, shall
17 receive a report of the results of the requested investigation. The
18 person or entity requesting the investigation may give that
19 information only to the appropriate prosecutorial officer or agency
20 having statutory authority in the matter if that action appears
21 proper from the information contained in the report, and shall not
22 reveal or give such information to any other person or agency.
23 Violation hereof shall be deemed willful neglect of duty and shall
24 be grounds for removal from office.
Req. No. 3736 Page 4

1 3. Investigative records of the Bureau shall not be subject to
2 a subpoena or subpoena duces tecum in any private civil action
3 unless, after reasonable notice to the Bureau, or any authorized
4 governmental agency that has an interest in the information, after a
5 hearing, wherein the party issuing the subpoena demonstrates and a
6 court finds that the need for the record or records sought
7 substantially outweighs the presumption of the confidentiality of
8 such record or records and, further, upon making such a finding, a
9 court has determined that disclosure of the record or records would
10 not jeopardize any investigation by the Bureau or authorized
11 governmental agency that has an interest in the information. In the
12 event the court orders the dissemination of any record or part of a
13 record, the court shall enter a protective order consistent
14 herewith.
15 E. It shall not be a violation of this section to reveal
16 otherwise confidential information to outside agencies or
17 individuals who are providing interpreter services, questioned
18 document analysis, laboratory services, or other specialized
19 services that are necessary in the to or that may provide assistance
20 of in Bureau investigations. Individuals or agencies receiving the
21 confidential and investigative information or records or results of
22 laboratory services provided to the Bureau by those agencies or
23 individuals, shall be subject to the confidentiality provisions and
24 requirements established in subsection D of this section.
Req. No. 3736 Page 5

1 F. It shall not be a violation of this section to reveal for
2 training or educational purposes otherwise confidential information
3 from records relating to any investigation previously conducted by
4 the Bureau, including any records of laboratory services provided to
5 law enforcement agencies pursuant to paragraph 1 of subsection A of
6 Section 150.2 of this title, so long as ten (10) or more years have
7 passed since the production of the information or record or such
8 information or record relates to an investigation that is closed by
9 way of conviction or plea of guilty or nolo contendere.
10 G. It shall not be a violation of this section to reveal
11 otherwise confidential information from records relating to any
12 investigation being conducted by the Bureau, including any records
13 of laboratory services provided to law enforcement agencies pursuant
14 to paragraph 1 of subsection A of Section 150.2 of this title or to
15 the public, provided, release of the confidential information has
16 been authorized by the Director of the Bureau for the purposes of
17 developing or obtaining further information reasonably necessary to
18 the successful conclusion of a criminal investigation being
19 conducted by the Bureau or authorized by the Director of the Bureau
20 for the purpose of advising crime victims or family representatives
21 of homicide victims regarding the status of a pending investigation
22 or to provide a summary of a closed investigation when necessary.
23 H. The State Treasurer shall initiate a complete background
24 investigation of the positions with the written consent of the
Req. No. 3736 Page 6

1 pers ons who are the subject of the investigation pursuant to
2 subsection I of Section 71.1 of Title 62 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
3 The Bureau shall advise the State Treasurer and the Cash Management
4 and Investment Oversight Commission Invest in Oklahoma Board in
5 writing of the results of the investigation.
6 I. The Bureau may report statistical data that does not include
7 personal information to law enforcement and the public. As
8 authorized by the Director, the Bureau may also enter into
9 agreements with federal, state, county, tribal, or municipal law
10 enforcement agencies for the dissemination of otherwise confidential
11 information from investigations or laboratory services conducted by
12 the Bureau where the purpose of the information disseminated is in
13 furtherance of criminal investigations and crime prevention.
14 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 74 O.S. 2021, Section 150.7, is
15 amended to read as follows:
16 Section 150.7. The Director of the Oklahoma State Bureau of
17 Investigation shall have the following powers, duties, and
18 responsibilities:
19 1. To appoint or dismiss a Deputy Director to assist in the
20 administration of the Bureau;
21 2. To supervise the maintaining of all reports and records of
22 the Bureau and to promulgate administrative rules concerning the
23 destruction and retention of such records. Such records shall not
24 be transferred to the custody or control of the Archives and Records
Req. No. 3736 Page 7

1 Comm ission or be subject to the provisions of Section 590 of Title
2 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes or the Records Management Act. The
3 Director may, pursuant to adopted and promulgated administrative
4 rule, order destruction of records deemed to be no longer of value
5 to the Bureau, excluding criminalistic and investigative records
6 which shall forever be kept and maintained. The Director may cause
7 any or all original papers or records kept by the Bureau to be
8 digitally scanned or imaged and stored on a computer or digital
9 storage medium in lieu of retention of the original records or
10 papers. However, the digitally stored records or papers shall be an
11 accurate and complete reproduction of the original papers or records
12 and stored in a conveniently accessible manner. Following the
13 scanning, imaging, and digital storage of the original records or
14 papers, the Director may authorize the disposal, archival storage,
15 or destruction of the original records or papers;
16 3. To report to the Commission at each regular meeting, or as
17 directed by the Commission, the current workload of the Bureau.
18 Such reports shall be submitted by category of the persons or
19 entities authorized to initiate investigations as provided for in
20 subsection A of Section 150.5 of this title, and any other category
21 the Commission may request which does not violate the
22 confidentiality restrictions imposed in Sections 150.1 through 152.9
23 152.12 of this title. Such reports shall contain the following
24 information:
Req. No. 3736 Page 8

1 a. what the types of investigations that are pending,
2 b. what the new types of investigations that have been
3 opened,
4 c. what the types of investigations that have been
5 closed, and
6 d. what the criminal charges that have been filed as a
7 result of Bureau investigations.
8 The reports shall not contain any information on the individual
9 subjects of the investigation or persons questioned in connection
10 with an investigation. These reports shall be open for public
11 inspection;
12 4. To designate positions, appoint employees, and fix salaries
13 of the Bureau, other than the salaries established by subsection A
14 of Section 150.6a of this title, and to authorize the payment of
15 necessary certification expenses for the employees;
16 5. To authorize the purchase and issuance of uniforms for all
17 law enforcement officers, criminalists, and other personnel of the
18 Bureau as designated by the Director and to purchase and issue
19 necessary equipment for all employees of the Bureau. All uniforms
20 and equipment shall be used only in the performance of the official
21 duties of the officers, criminalists, or other personnel and shall
22 remain the property of the Bureau except as otherwise provided by
23 law;
24
Req. No. 3736 Page 9

1 6. To accept gifts, bequests, devises, contributions, and
2 grants, whether public or private, including funds from federal and
3 state agencies, or funds from any other source for use in furthering
4 the operations of the Bureau. All monies received by the Director
5 pursuant to this subsection shall be deposited to the credit of the
6 OSBI Revolving Fund;
7 7. To enter into local cooperative agreements with local law
8 enforcement agencies for the purpose of appointing affiliate task
9 force agents to assist the Bureau in the investigation of major
10 crimes under the jurisdiction of the Bureau. Affiliate task force
11 agents shall be employees and commissioned law enforcement officers
12 of the local law enforcement agency entering into agreement with the
13 Bureau and shall not be employees of the Bureau. Affiliate task
14 force agents shall have general peace officer powers and the
15 authority to arrest persons throughout the state while serving as an
16 affiliate task force agent. Affiliate task force agents serve
17 solely at the discretion and will of the Director. The Director may
18 renew, suspend, or revoke any agreement appointing an affiliate task
19 force agent at any time; and
20 7. 8. To enter into interagency transfers with the Oklahoma
21 Highway Patrol, the Oklahoma State Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous
22 Drugs Control, and the Oklahoma Alcoholic Beverages Beverage Laws
23 Enforcement Commission as provided for in Section 1 of this act
24 Section 11000 of this title.
Req. No. 3736 Page 10

1 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 74 O.S. 2021, Section 150.11, is
2 amended to read as follows:
3 Section 150.11. A. All Except as provided for in Section
4 1024.4 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes, all property which
5 comes into the possession of the Oklahoma State Bureau of
6 Investigation (OSBI), whether the same is stolen, embezzled, or
7 otherwise, which the Bureau has held for at least one (1) year
8 unless said the property is perishable, may be disposed of by order
9 of an Oklahoma County district court if the owner or owners of said
10 the property are unknown or have not claimed the same. The Director
11 of the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation shall then be
12 authorized to sell, deposit, donate, destroy, or otherwise dispose
13 of such property or any part thereof which is no longer needed to be
14 held as evidence or otherwise used in connection with any
15 litigation.
16 B. 1. If cash or other legal tender is the subject of the
17 action, the Director shall file a petition in the district court of
18 Oklahoma County requesting authority to forfeit and deposit the
19 funds. The petition shall include the following information:
20 a. description of the property,
21 b. approximate date that the property came into
22 possession of the Director, and
23 c. the names of the owner or owners, if known.
24
Req. No. 3736 Page 11

1 2. Upon the filing of the petition, notice of at least ten (10)
2 days shall be given to each known owner by the Director of the OSBI
3 by mailing a copy of the petition and notice of hearing to the last-
4 known address of each owner by certified mail.
5 3. Notice of the hearing shall also be posted at the Oklahoma
6 County courthouse at the regular place assigned for the posting of
7 legal notices and in the public lobby at OSBI headquarters.
8 4. If no owner appears and establishes ownership to the cash or
9 legal tender, the court shall enter an order authorizing the
10 forfeiture of the funds to the OSBI. All monies forfeited shall be
11 deposited into the OSBI Revolving Fund.
12 C. 1. For disposition of all other seized property, the
13 Director shall file a petition in the district court of Oklahoma
14 County requesting authority to conduct a sale of, or otherwise
15 dispose of, the property as provided herein. The petition shall
16 include the following information:
17 a. description of the property,
18 b. approximate date that the property came into the
19 possession of the Director, and
20 c. the names of the owner or owners, if known.
21 2. Upon the filing of the petition, notice of at least ten (10)
22 days shall be given to each known owner by the Director of the OSBI
23 by mailing a copy of the petition and notice of hearing by certified
24 mail to the last-known address of each owner. An affidavit of
Req. No. 3736 Page 12

1 noti ce being sent shall be filed with the court by a representative
2 of the OSBI.
3 3. Notice of the hearing shall also be posted at the Oklahoma
4 County courthouse at the regular place assigned for the posting of
5 legal notices and in the public lobby at OSBI headquarters.
6 4. If no owner appears and establishes ownership to the
7 property, the court shall may enter an order authorizing the
8 Director to sell the property at public auction or Internet auction,
9 which may include online bidding, to the highest bidder after notice
10 of at least five (5) days of the auction has been given by
11 publication in one issue of a legal newspaper of record in Oklahoma
12 County. If the property is offered for sale at public auction,
13 including an Internet auction, and no bid is received that exceeds
14 fifty percent (50%) of the fair-market value of the property, such
15 value to be announced prior to the sale, the Director may refuse to
16 sell the item pursuant to any bid received.
17 5. The In the event of the sale of the property, the Director
18 shall make a return of sale, and when confirmed by the court, the
19 order confirming the sale shall vest title of the property to the
20 purchaser. The money received from the sale shall be deposited in
21 the OSBI Revolving Fund.
22 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
